# Configuration Externalization Pattern

When core contains hardcoded values that should vary between consuming projects (metro-one-cop, metro-one-tim, demo, etc.), use this pattern to externalize the configuration.

## When to Use

- AWS resource names (ECS clusters, services, S3 buckets)
- GitHub repository names
- Project-specific URLs or endpoints
- Feature flags that differ by project
- Any hardcoded values that are project-specific

## Architecture Overview

```mermaid
flowchart TB
    subgraph ConsumingProject [Consuming Project]
        ProjectConfig[Project config definition]
        ServerInit[initializeServer with config]
        AppLayout[AppProvider with config props]
    end
    
    subgraph Core [Core Package]
        Types[Type definitions only]
        ServerConfig[ServerConfig interface]
        AppProvider[AppProviderProps interface]
        ServerCode[Server code uses getServer]
        ClientCode[Client code uses useAppContext]
    end
    
    ProjectConfig --> ServerInit
    ProjectConfig --> AppLayout
    ServerInit --> ServerConfig
    AppLayout --> AppProvider
    ServerConfig --> ServerCode
    AppProvider --> ClientCode
```

## Step 1: Define Types in Core

Keep type definitions in core, remove hardcoded values:

```typescript
// src/lib/core/common/types/MyConfig.ts

export interface MyConfigItem {
  name: string;
  endpoint: string;
  label: string;
}

export type MyConfigMap = Record<string, MyConfigItem>;
```

Export from the common package:

```typescript
// src/venky-exports/core/common/index.ts
export type { MyConfigItem, MyConfigMap } from '@/lib/core/common/types/MyConfig';
```

## Step 2: Add to ServerConfig (Server-Side)

```typescript
// src/lib/core/server/ServerConfig.ts

import type { MyConfigMap } from '@/lib/core/common/types/MyConfig';

export interface ServerConfig {
  // ... existing fields
  myConfig?: MyConfigMap;
  myConfigOption?: string;
}
```

## Step 3: Add to AppProvider (Client-Side)

```typescript
// src/components/sidebar/app-provider.tsx

export interface AppContextValue {
  // ... existing fields
  myConfig?: MyConfigMap;
  myConfigOption?: string;
}

export interface AppProviderProps extends Partial<AppContextValue> {
  // ... existing fields
}
```

## Step 4: Update Server Code to Use Config

```typescript
// Server action or API route

import { getServer } from '@/lib/core/server/getServer';
import { UserError } from 'venky-core/common';

export async function myServerAction(/* ... */) {
  const server = getServer('myServerAction');
  const config = server.config.myConfig;
  
  // Throw error if config not provided by consuming project
  if (!config) {
    throw new UserError('myConfig not configured. Please configure in consuming project.');
  }
  
  // Use config
  const item = config['KEY'];
  // ...
}
```

## Step 5: Update Client Code to Use Context

Create a dedicated hook for the config:

```typescript
// src/components/core/hooks/useMyConfig.ts

import { useAppContext } from '@/components/sidebar/app-provider';

export function useMyConfig() {
  const { myConfig, myConfigOption } = useAppContext();
  
  if (!myConfig) {
    throw new Error('myConfig not configured. Please pass myConfig prop to AppProvider.');
  }
  
  return { myConfig, myConfigOption };
}
```

Use in components:

```typescript
// Component using the config

import { useMyConfig } from '@/components/core/hooks/useMyConfig';

export function MyComponent() {
  const { myConfig, myConfigOption } = useMyConfig();
  
  return (
    <div>
      {Object.entries(myConfig).map(([key, item]) => (
        <a key={key} href={item.endpoint}>{item.label}</a>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Step 6: Consuming Project Setup

### Define Configuration

```typescript
// In consuming project: lib/config/my-config.ts

import type { MyConfigMap } from 'venky-core/common';

export const MY_CONFIG_OPTION = 'option-value';

export const myConfig: MyConfigMap = {
  KEY1: {
    name: 'key1-name',
    endpoint: 'https://example.com/key1',
    label: 'Key 1',
  },
  KEY2: {
    name: 'key2-name',
    endpoint: 'https://example.com/key2',
    label: 'Key 2',
  },
};
```

### Pass to Server Initialization

```typescript
// In consuming project: lib/server/init/server-config.ts

import type { ServerConfig } from 'venky-core/server';
import { myConfig, MY_CONFIG_OPTION } from '@/lib/config/my-config';

const serverConfig: ServerConfig = {
  // ... other config
  myConfig,
  myConfigOption: MY_CONFIG_OPTION,
};

export default serverConfig;
```

### Pass to AppProvider

```typescript
// In consuming project: app/(secure)/layout.tsx

import { AppProvider } from 'venky-core/ui';
import { myConfig, MY_CONFIG_OPTION } from '@/lib/config/my-config';

export default function SecureLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <AppProvider
      myConfig={myConfig}
      myConfigOption={MY_CONFIG_OPTION}
    >
      {children}
    </AppProvider>
  );
}
```

## Error Handling

Always throw clear errors when config is missing:

```typescript
// Server-side
if (!config) {
  throw new UserError('Feature X requires myConfig. Configure in your project\'s ServerConfig.');
}

// Client-side
if (!myConfig) {
  throw new Error('Feature X requires myConfig prop on AppProvider.');
}
```

## Disabling Workflow

Not all consuming projects need the workflow feature.

1. **YAML** – Set `features: { workflow: false }` in `config/default.yml` (or `config/env.yml` for env-specific). The job registry reads this via `getConfig()` at load time and does not add the four workflow jobs to the default list, so they are not scheduled.

2. **Sidebar teams** – Core does not gate teams by config. In your server-config, pass a `teams` array that excludes the workflow portal, e.g. `[adminPortal, chatPortal]` (import from `venky-core/server/sidebar`), so the Workflows team does not appear in the sidebar.

3. **Layout** – Omit `workflowPlugins` or pass `workflowPlugins={[]}` to AppProvider. Apps that don’t use workflow don’t pass plugins.

Workflow jobs will not run, the Workflows team will not appear (if you pass teams without it), and no workflow client plugins will register. DataSources and routes remain available; optional route/API guards can be added in the consuming project if desired.

## Natural language SmartSearch

NL/voice search on table filter bars is gated in three layers (deployment capability, optional app default, per-page override).

1. **YAML (opt-out)** — NL/voice parse is enabled at deployment level unless `features.naturalLanguageSearch: false` in `config/default.yml` (or `config/env.yml`). Omitted or `true` allows parse. Server: `isNaturalLanguageSearchEnabled()` (`!== false`). Client: `naturalLanguageSearchEnabled` on `AppContext` (`naturalLanguageSearchEnabledProp ?? features.naturalLanguageSearch !== false`).

2. **App default (optional)** — Pass `DEFAULT_ENABLE_NATURAL_LANGUAGE_SEARCH={true}` on `AppProvider` / `BaseAppProvider` to enable NL on all pages that do not pass an explicit prop. Defaults to `false` (`ENABLE_NATURAL_LANGUAGE_SEARCH_DEFAULT` in `@/lib/common/ui-constants`).

3. **Per page (opt-in or override)** — On list pages using `PageLayoutTemplate`, pass `enableNaturalLanguageSearch` (and optionally `nlPlaceholder`). On direct `SmartSearch` usage, pass the same prop on `SmartSearch` or `TableFilters`. Omitted prop uses the app default; pass `false` to opt out when the app default is on.

4. **Disable deployment-wide** — Set `features.naturalLanguageSearch: false`. The parse action rejects with a clear `UserError`; the mode toggle never appears regardless of app or page props.

Optional: pass `naturalLanguageSearchEnabled={true|false}` on `AppProvider` to override the value from config (rare; for tests or special layouts).

See `AGENTS.md` for natural-language SmartSearch configuration and verification.

## Checklist

- [ ] Types defined in `@/lib/core/common/types/`
- [ ] Types exported from `venky-core/common`
- [ ] `ServerConfig` interface updated
- [ ] `AppContextValue` and `AppProviderProps` updated
- [ ] Server code uses `getServer().config` with error handling
- [ ] Client hook created with error handling
- [ ] Client components use the hook
- [ ] Documentation updated for consuming projects

## Files to Modify

| Location | File | Purpose |
|----------|------|---------|
| Core | `src/lib/core/common/types/MyConfig.ts` | Type definitions |
| Core | `src/venky-exports/core/common/index.ts` | Export types |
| Core | `src/lib/core/server/ServerConfig.ts` | Add to server config |
| Core | `src/components/sidebar/app-provider.tsx` | Add to client context |
| Core | `src/components/core/hooks/useMyConfig.ts` | Client access hook |
| Consuming | `lib/config/my-config.ts` | Config values |
| Consuming | `lib/server/init/server-config.ts` | Pass to server |
| Consuming | `app/(secure)/layout.tsx` | Pass to AppProvider |
